Andy Burnham will have to decide what “social media” actually means.

LONDON — One of Keir Starmer’s final acts before he announced his resignation as prime minister was to unveil a social media ban for under-16s .

As Starmer prepares to hand over power to prime-minister-in-waiting Andy Burnham,&nbsp;he’ll&nbsp;also be handing over the hardest part of the ban — figuring out&nbsp;how it will&nbsp;actually work.&nbsp;

Starmer’s Tech Secretary Liz Kendall&nbsp;gave an update on Wednesday,&nbsp;filling in&nbsp;some of the gaps on the&nbsp;policy since&nbsp;Starmer’s top-line announcement last month. But some&nbsp;big, thorny question marks&nbsp;remain.&nbsp;

This&nbsp;may seem an obvious question,&nbsp;but&nbsp;it’s&nbsp;the million-dollar one&nbsp;from a legal and regulatory perspective&nbsp;— and still&nbsp;hasn’t&nbsp;been worked out.&nbsp;&nbsp;

Part of the challenge for officials is that “social media” isn’t a statutory term or regulated category of service under the Online Safety Act , meaning they’ll need to decide which platforms count (and why) without relying on existing legislation.

All the household name platforms the government has already confirmed will be caught by the ban (including Instagram, TikTok and YouTube) are currently regulated as “user-to-user services,” because they allow people to generate and share content for others to see. But so are platforms like eBay, Etsy, and Wikipedia — and many others besides, from online marketplaces to dating apps.

Last month DSIT&nbsp;said&nbsp;the definition would be inspired by Australia’s social media ban for children ,&nbsp;covering&nbsp;user-to-user services&nbsp;“whose purpose is to enable social interaction, alongside algorithms.”&nbsp;

This leaves a lot of room for interpretation.&nbsp;Tech lawyers are&nbsp; warning&nbsp;clients &nbsp;— and prospective clients&nbsp;— not to get too comfortable,&nbsp;especially since the&nbsp;department&nbsp;is yet to produce&nbsp;any further details about the “narrowly defined list of exemptions” promised last month.&nbsp;&nbsp;

Whatever criteria&nbsp;the government&nbsp;lands&nbsp;on&nbsp;needs to be coherent&nbsp;enough that it&nbsp;stands up to scrutiny&nbsp;if in-scope services start asking&nbsp;why their competitors have been left out.&nbsp;

Defining “social media” is one thing; deciding&nbsp; how &nbsp;to ban it is&nbsp;another beast altogether.&nbsp;

One&nbsp;method&nbsp;is to give companies the option of proving that their platforms are safe&nbsp;enough for kids.&nbsp;

Canada provides an alternative blueprint to Australia.&nbsp;&nbsp;

Canada’s&nbsp;proposal &nbsp;allows&nbsp;its&nbsp;regulator to exempt&nbsp;platforms&nbsp;if they can&nbsp;demonstrate&nbsp;having “adequate safeguards” in place&nbsp;to protect children.&nbsp;&nbsp;

Kendall ruled out similar workarounds last week.&nbsp;“Maybe new types of things will become available, but if they fulfil the criteria that we have set out for defining social media ...&nbsp;then they will not be allowed to provide those services to kids under 16,” she told MPs on the Science, Innovation and Technology Committee.&nbsp;&nbsp;
